 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fatal-revision",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "This work is licensed under a [Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International License](http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/).\n",
    "\n",
    "# Optimal hard threshold for singular values\n",
    "\n",
    "This notebook demonstrates the effect of rank-truncation on noise in the data. We show how the automatic estimation of the optimal rank simplifies the truncation. The notebook's content is based on the following two resources, where the first resource is an excellent Pyton-based tutorial on the optimal SVD-HT (SVD Hard Threshold) by Robert Taylor, and the second resource is a research article covering the theory behind the optimal rank selection used here:\n",
    "\n",
    "1. Robert Taylor: [Optimal Singular Value Hard Threshold](http://www.pyrunner.com/weblog/2016/08/01/optimal-svht/), PyRunner Webblog, 2016\n",
    "2. M. Gavish and D. L. Donoho, The Optimal Hard Threshold for Singular Values is $4/\\sqrt {3}$, IEEE Transactions on Information Theory, vol. 60, no. 8, pp. 5040-5053, Aug. 2014, doi: [10.1109/TIT.2014.2323359](https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/document/6846297)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "simple-sampling",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import torch as pt\n",
    "import matplotlib as mpl\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from flowtorch.analysis import SVD\n",
    "\n",
    "# increase resolution of plots\n",
    "mpl.rcParams['figure.dpi'] = 160"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "hollywood-beads",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Creating the data matrix\n",
    "\n",
    "The data matrix is assembled from two superimposed functions and some added white Gaussian noise."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "atmospheric-rally",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 960x640 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "x = pt.linspace(-10, 10, 100)\n",
    "t = pt.linspace(0, 20, 200)\n",
    "Xm, Tm = pt.meshgrid(x, t)\n",
    "\n",
    "data_matrix = 5.0 / pt.cosh(0.5*Xm) * pt.tanh(0.5*Xm) * pt.exp(1.5j*Tm) # primary mode\n",
    "data_matrix += 0.5 * pt.sin(2.0*Xm) * pt.exp(2.0j*Tm) # secondary mode\n",
    "data_matrix += 0.5 * pt.normal(mean=pt.zeros_like(Xm), std=pt.ones_like(Xm))\n",
    "\n",
    "# plot data matrix as image\n",
    "plt.imshow(data_matrix.real)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"t\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"x\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "express-fossil",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Singular value decomposition with hard threshold\n",
    "\n",
    "First, let's examine the singular value distribution without rank truncation. Since we created the data with two spatial modes, there should be only two singular values different from zero."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "prepared-bloom",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "SVD of a 100x200 data matrix\n",
      "Selected/optimal rank: 100/2\n",
      "data type: torch.complex64 (8b)\n",
      "truncated SVD size: 234.7656Kb\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "svd = SVD(data_matrix, 100)\n",
    "print(svd)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "demographic-sunrise",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Examining the SVD meta data printed above, we can see that an optimal threshold of two was estimated, but we chose a rank of 100. Let's plot the singular value distribution and show the optimal truncation."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "skilled-diagram",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 960x640 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "color = [\"C0\" if s <= svd.s[2] else \"C1\" for s in svd.s]\n",
    "plt.bar(range(svd.s.shape[0]), svd.s, color=color)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(r\"$i$\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(r\"$\\sigma_i$\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "apparent-greensboro",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The additional non-zero singular values result from the added Gaussian noise. Now we perform the SVD again, but this time with automatic rank truncation. Note that we could also use the previously computed SVD and do the truncation manually. The truncated SVD is significantly smaller than its full counterpart."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "indian-essex",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "name": "stdout",
     "output_type": "stream",
     "text": [
      "SVD of a 100x200 data matrix\n",
      "Selected/optimal rank: 2/2\n",
      "data type: torch.complex64 (8b)\n",
      "truncated SVD size: 4.6953Kb\n"
     ]
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "svd = SVD(data_matrix)\n",
    "print(svd)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "valuable-airport",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can now reconstruct the full data based on the truncated SVD. Since we cut off the noisy modes, the SVD acts as a denoising tool in this application."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "under-tuition",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 960x640 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "reconstruction = svd.U @ pt.diag(svd.s).type(pt.complex64) @ svd.V.conj().T\n",
    "plt.imshow(reconstruction.real)\n",
    "plt.xlabel(\"t\")\n",
    "plt.ylabel(\"x\")\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "accredited-incidence",

   "source": []
  }
